  1. Use transition_reveal to make a plot revealing the number of deaths in the three countries with the most numbers of deaths
library(gganimate)
library(ggplot2)
library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
df %>% filter(Date_reported == max(Date_reported)) %>% arrange(-Cumulative_deaths) %>% top_n(3,Cumulative_deaths) 
## # A tibble: 3  8
##   Date_reported Country_code Country     WHO_r New_c Cumul New_d Cumul
##   <date>        <chr>        <chr>       <chr>     <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1 2022-10-12    US           United Sta AMRO      26039  9.54e7     148 1051649
## 2 2022-10-12    BR           Brazil      AMRO       4682  3.47e7      26  686877
## 3 2022-10-12    IN           India       SEARO      2139  4.46e7      13  528835
## #  with abbreviated variable names WHO_region, New_cases, Cumulative_cases,
## #   New_deaths, Cumulative_deaths
plot1 <- df %>% filter(Country %in% c('United States of America','Brazil','India')) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y=Cumulative_deaths,
            x=Date_reported,
            color=Country))+ 
  geom_line()+
  geom_point(size=3)+
  transition_reveal(Date_reported)
plot1

  1. Create the new variable (column) death_per_cases recording the number of deaths per cases (Hint: divide cumulative deaths by cumulative cases). What are the three countries with the highest deaths per cases?
df$death_per_cases = df$Cumulative_deaths / df$Cumulative_cases
df %>% filter(Date_reported == max(Date_reported)) %>% arrange(-death_per_cases) %>% top_n(3,death_per_cases)

  1. Use transition_reveal to make a plot revealing the number of deaths per cases of the US, Italy and Mexico.
plot <- df %>% filter(Country %in% c('United States of America','Italy','Mexico')) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y=death_per_cases,
            x=Date_reported,
            color=Country))+ 
  geom_line()+
  geom_point(size=3)+
  transition_reveal(Date_reported)
plot

  1. Import the following data https://raw.githubusercontent.com/owid/covid-19-data/master/public/data/vaccinations/vaccinations.csv

Use transition_reveal to plot the total vaccinations per hundred by level of income. Hint: the levels of income are identified in the location variable. Put a short comment on the caption of the plot.

df <- read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/owid/covid-19-data/master/public/data/vaccinations/vaccinations.csv")

plot <- df %>% filter(location %in% c("Lower middle income", "Low income", "Upper middle income")) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y=total_vaccinations_per_hundred,
            x=date,
            color=location))+ 
  geom_line()+
  geom_point(size=1)+
  transition_reveal(date)+
  labs(caption = 'R is infact a pretty cool software')
plot
